ONE FINAL BATTLE TO SAVE THE ALAMO CENOTAPH

Lee White, President and Founder of the Alamo Defenders Descendants Association sent us this plea.

‚ÄúThe direct descendants of the Alamo are fighting as our ancestors once did against tyranny. The politicians didn‚Äôt deliver safety for the Alamo Cenotaph nor insurance that the Defender story wouldn‚Äôt be diminished.

‚ÄúFolks! This is the last stand . . .
‚ÄúWill you come to our aid or will it end as it did in 1836? We can prevail in Federal Court but we need funds. Please send what you can as the enemy are upon us. Share this post and donate.

Make out checks or money orders to:
Alamo Defenders Descendants Association 
Mailing address:
Lee White
P.O. Box 856
Freer, Texas 78357
‚ÄúTogether we can win!‚Äù

Because we have fought for three years to save the Alamo‚Äîand the Cenotaph specifically‚Äîfrom the indignities that George P. Bush‚Äôs Reimagine the Alamo plan entails, we have agreed to support the Alamo Defenders Descendants Association‚Äôs (ADDA) effort.

To give newcomers a thumbnail sketch of our fight, I will highlight the details.

1) While we don‚Äôt object to all elements of the plan, when we learned that Texas General Land Office (GLO) Commissioner Bush planned not to only restore or repair the Alamo complex, but to reimagine it instead, at a cost of $450 million, our campaign began.

2) First, we created a social media and public media campaign to let all Texans understand that the shrine could be respectfully restored for about one-tenth the cost and the plan to do so already existed. Building a social media platform and attracting followers takes time‚Äîtime we didn‚Äôt have. Moreover, most of our appeals to public media fell on deaf ears.

3) In the 2018 Texas Election, George P. Bush again ran for Texas GLO Commissioner. Defeating him would have halted the Reimagine plan, but that did not happen. We asked for your financial support to broadcast our message statewide, but only a few generous followers responded. That effort failed‚ÄîBush‚Äôs plan moved forward.

4) We tried again whenever several monument protection bills were presented to the 86th Texas Legislature in 2019. Thanks to tremendous response from our followers who wrote, emailed, and called Texas officials when we asked, we got one perfect bill that had passed through the Senate, a House committee, and awaited a spot on the calendar for House floor vote. Political betrayal at the last moment killed the bill.

Alongside us, Lee White and the ADDA campaigned against moving the Cenotaph with good reason. In 2014, the General Land Office commissioned an analysis of the fitness of the Alamo Cenotaph. In that report, it was considered in good condition and should be restored in place rather than moved. George P. Bush took office in 2015 and had other plans. That restoration didn‚Äôt happen.

Even though that report warned against irreparable damage if it were moved, Bush‚Äôs Reimagine plan calls for the Cenotaph to be moved from its present location‚Äîin front of the Long Barracks where the Alamo defenders made their last stand, and where most of them died‚Äîto an area to the south that is completely outside the Alamo perimeter. 

In her tireless effort, Lee discovered State Health and Safety Code, Chapter 711 whereby any piece of land can be officially designated as an ‚Äúunverified cemetery‚Äù if it contains human remains or unmarked graves. Such designation invokes mandatory regulations that would prevent moving the Cenotaph. Bush‚Äôs people opposed that designation of Alamo Plaza at a recent Texas Historical Commission (THC) meeting, stating that if so designated, it would stop them from implementing the Reimagine the Alamo Master Plan. The THC therefore denied the official designation as Bush requested, instead granting ‚Äúhonorary cemetery‚Äù status that lacks all the stringent requirements.
The Plaza qualifies under the terms of the Chapter 711 state law, since numerous verified human remains have been found in archaeological excavations, some of them likely remains of the Alamo defenders. In addition, upwards of 1,500 mission Indians are buried in unmarked graves in the Plaza as documented in the Alamo Mission Spanish Inventories. 

As bloodline descendants of the Alamo defenders, Lee White and the ADDA have legal standing to file this action in both State and Federal District Courts. We do not. They plan to file in Federal Court, and if the case proceeds to trial, they will invoke their right to a trial by JURY. As part of this lawsuit, they will seek a Temporary Injunction (TI) to prevent any action by Bush against the Alamo Cenotaph pending resolution of the case in court on the merits. Once applied for, a TI is considered an emergency by the court and is ruled on almost immediately. If granted, the TI will place a mantle of protection over the Cenotaph throughout the life of the case, including any appeals.

Lee has engaged an excellent law firm at a greatly reduced rate. Nonetheless, going to court costs money. The lawyers have done the background work and made all preparations to file the lawsuit. Lee must have an additional $10,000 IN HAND to file the suit and the application for the protective injunction. This may sound like a lot of money, and it is.
